msDesc.head: Philosophical treatises and medical tracts and recipes

summary.seg: This 15th-century English manuscript contains a collection of philosophical treatises, and medical tracts and recipes, largely written in Latin but also containing a few Middle English recipes on its opening page. The Latin recipes had previously not been studied in detail before but they contain valuable information with which it is possible to date and locate the manuscript's origins more precisely, and to consider the socio-historical context of its production and use.

The recipes often refer to well-known medical authorities, such as Gilbert Kymer (d. 1463), physician to Humphrey of Lancaster, 1st Duke of Gloucester, and Thomas Duncan (fl. c. 1400-1461), physician to Edmund Mortimer, 5th Earl of March. However, their composer also regularly provides anecdotes from and refers to obscure medical practitioners who were local to North Yorkshire. For example, a recipe for an unstated purpose is said to have been proved by 'a nun of Sheriff Hutton' (f. 150r), referring to a village of that name situated to the north-east of York and probably specifically to a member of the nearby Augustinian nunnery at what is now Marton-cum-Moxby, known as Moxby Priory. A recipe against icterus (f. 192v) that is said to have been used by Elizabeth Scrop may refer to a member of the Scropes of Bolton, West Yorkshire, or of Masham, North Yorkshire. A cure for migraine (f. 195v) is attributed to a certain John Richardson who is located near Whitby, North Yorkshire, while another for stomach pain (f. 196r) is attributed to a Henry Haxby of York. A medicine for a swelling (f. 196r) is said to have been used on the wife of 'Peter Bukton of Pickering Lithe' (perhaps Peter Bukton (1350-1414), steward and master forester of the lordship of Holderness, member of parliament for Yorkshire, constable of Knaresborough Castle, Justice of the Peace in the East Riding, High Sheriff of Yorkshire; mayor of the city of Bordeaux in Southern France, and addressee of Geoffrey Chaucer's Lenvoy de Chaucer a Bukton). She is said to have been carried to York where she was placed under the care of two friars named 'Tatman' and 'Multon' (f. 196r). The latter is elsewhere mentioned in the manuscript (in a recipe for diatessaron) and there credited as 'P. Multon of York' (f. 101v). While he cannot be identified with certainty, friar 'Tatman' almost certainly is Robert Tatman, a Dominican friar of York who was parson of the church of Scrayingham in East Yorkshire and Master of the Hospital of God at Greatham in the South of Durham, in 1439. None of the aforementioned practitioners and patients can be found in C.H. Talbot and E.A. Hammond, The Medical Practitioners in Medieval England: A Biographical Register (London: Wellcome Historical Medical Library, 1965). Their obscurity may well owe to the location of the compiler(s) of the recipes and the local sources from which they drew their medical knowledge.

Probably less indicative of the specific locality in which the medical recipes were compiled but providing further evidence for the collection's regional provenance are the medicines that are associated with figures from across Northern England. These include a recipe against diarrhoea (f. 101v) that is attributed to a deacon of Lancaster; a recipe against the plague (ff. 101v-102r) that is said to have been made for E. de nevyl, perhaps Eleanor Neville (d. 1472), Countess of Northumberland; a faded recipe (f. 178v) attributed to the 'physician of Southwell', referring to Southwell, Nottinghamshire; a recipe against paralysis (f. 195r) that is attributed to T. Poppos [? Popes] who is identified as a former 'vicar of Stranton', referring to Stranton in Durham; a recipe (f. 195v) that is attributed to the physician William Cawdray (d. 1434) of Pontefract, West Yorkshire [see Talbot and Hammond (1965), p. 391] and that the compiler claims to have learnt from "Belton the apothecary" (almost certainly the same Robert Belton of York who, as an experienced apothecary, was asked to arbitrate when the prior of Guisborough Priory in North Yorkshire tried to sue Matthew Rillesford, a medical practitioner from York, for his negligence in treating one of the monastery’s brothers in the year 1433); and a recipe against disease (f. 196r) that is attributed to Thomas Wilton (fl. c. 1381-1448), a physician in the York diocese [see Talbot and Hammond (1965), pp. 361-362].

The recipes not only suggest that the manuscript originates from North East Yorkshire but also that the manuscript was produced in or after 1421: recipes on f. 102r and f. 194v) are dated to this year.

The identity of the compiler(s) is unknown but on f. 165r a physician writing in the first person refers to themselves as G. when claiming to have used a particular recipe to cure a Cistercian monk (unum monacum album) from sciatica. The fact that the collection refers to a number of monastic physicians and patients and that the manuscript also contains a few devotional and theological items make it possible that the manuscript was made in a milieu that was located at or associated with a religious institution.
summary.p: For more details on the friars mentioned in this manuscript, see Peter Murray Jones, ‘Friars and Healing Remedies in Fifteenth Century York’ (forthcoming).

foliation.note: Numbering in pencil in the upper right-hand corner of the rectos.

Non-sequential foliation (restarting in each quire) in ink at the center of the upper margin of selected rectos: '36' (f. 45); '17'-'26' (ff. 74-83); '16'-'17' (ff. 99-100); '19'-'31' (ff. 101-113); '27'-'[34]' (ff. 140-147); '1'-'24' (ff. 155-178); '1'-'27' (ff. 179-205).

collation.formula: 110 238-1 (3rd leaf missing) 336 430-1 (17th leaf missing) 534 68-1 (8th leaf missing) 724 828

note.p: This collation deviates from that of James (1895) who counts 32 leaves in quire 4 by considering the fragmentary paper strip that has been foliated as f. 85 as the remains of a complete separate leaf and by considering f. 113 as two leaves: a fragmentary paper strip pasted on a complete paper leaf. However, the latter is almost certainly a longer leaf that has been folded to fit the dimensions of this manuscript. Folio 85 appears to have been the foldover of another longer leaf that has become detached from its original leaf. This is almost certainly f. 84, which contains the torn remains of a paper flap in a pattern that is identical to the torn upper edge of f. 85. This is also supported by the fact that f. 84 forms a bifolum with f. 113. This bifolium originates from a paperstock that is different from the rest of the manuscript as it features a watermark (a flower with 7 petals) that is not elsewhere found in the manuscript. Although this record does count f. 84 and 85 as two separate leaves in the description of the manuscript's extent (as both leaves have been foliated separately), it assumes that the two leaves originally formed one leaf like the flap that is still attached to f. 113. This changes James's count of the leaves in quire 4 from 32 to 30.

signatures.p: Medieval quire letters written at the centre of the upper margins of the first rectos of quires ["C" (Quire 3), "D" (Quire 4), "ff" (Quire 5), "G" (Quire 6), "H" (Quire 7), "J" (Quire 8)], except for quire 1 which does not have a letter and quire 2 which has "A" written on its 5th leaf (parchment), suggesting that the quire originally was planned to have 30 leaves but that four outer bifolia were subsequently added.

layout.seg: Ruled in leadpoint, frame only. 24-29 lines to the page, written below top line.

handNote.p: Copied by several scribes working in cursive scripts with both anglicana and secretary features.

decoNote.p: Drawings of a man or boy with a face on his belly, and two dogs playing with one another, in brown ink in the lower margin of f. 14r.
Two sketches of a (?) flower in brown ink on f. 47v.
Latin formula and incipits written inside decorative banderols in black ink (e.g. ff. 14r [empty], 37r, 38r, 38v, 48r, 48r).
Manicules in brown ink in margins throughout the manuscript.
One large (4 lines) plain initial in red ink on f. 115v.
Regular capitals (1 line) decorated with cadels in brown ink throughout the manuscript.
Regular capitals (1 line) highlighted in red ink on ff. 115v-118r.

binding.p: Original limp binding or wrapper made from different pieces of vellum with knots of rough leather cords on the spine that have been used for attaching the quires to the binding in a long stitch sewing pattern.

origin.origDate: Copied in the 15th century (in or after 1421).

history.acquisition: It is unknown how the manuscript was acquired by Jesus College: its armorial bookplate with the inscription: Collegium Jesu Cantabrigiense 1700 pasted on the inside of the upper cover; and its classmark 'Q G 23' printed on three lables pasted on the spine.
